@chapter Introduction

This manual describes the steps taken to create the VA2EPR Terminal
Node Controller. It includes details on everything from ordering components to
setting up and running the PC software. The aim of this document is to
provide a set of instructions that could be used to rebuild and use the device.

@chapter Obtaining Materials

One of the design goals of the project was to choose generic parts
and materials such that it would be easy to find parts and part suppliers. This
chapter will describe where parts were obtained and provide general
information about each of the suppliers. In each instance, I tried to choose
the best. most economical supplier.

@section Printed Circuit Boards (iTead Studio)

The printed circuit boards were fabricated by
@url{http://iteadstudio.com/,iTead Studio} in
Shenzhen, China. The cost was under $25 for 10 green boards which
measure 10cm x 10cm (or less) each. Shipping was under $10. After paying,
I e-mailed the @url{http://www.tomcort.com/va2epr-tnc/gerber.zip,GERBER} files
to iTead Studio. I got a response back saying they were sent to the factory.
It took about a week for the boards to be produced, and two weeks for the
PCBs to make it from China to Canada through the postal system. I've used
iTead Studio more than once, and I've always had good results.

@section Electronic Components (Digi-key)

I purchased all of the electronic components from
@url{http://digikey.ca,Digi-key}. The parts I ordered,
along with Digi-key part numbers, are listed in the
@url{http://www.tomcort.com/va2epr-tnc/materials.htm,Bill of Materials}.
Digi-key parts are relatively inexpensive and overnight shipping is $8.
I've never had a problem with a Digi-key order.

@section Enclosure (TenTec)

I purchased the enclosure from @url{http://tentec.com/,TenTec}. I went with
the TP-41 due to cost, but the TG-24 will also work. The prices was reasonable,
and the shipping was pretty fast.

